Lets take into case a continuous ParticleEffect with a single emitter. This is ParticleEffect's "isComplete" method:

public boolean isComplete () {
        for (int i = 0, n = emitters.size; i < n; i++) {
            ParticleEmitter emitter = emitters.get(i);
            if (!emitter.isComplete()) return false;
        }
        return true;
    }

This means that it depends on the emitter's completion. This is ParticleEmitter's "isComplete":

public boolean isComplete () {
        if (delayTimer < delay) return false;
        return durationTimer >= duration && activeCount == 0;
    }

It depends mostly on delayTimer, and if we check the update method of ParticleEmitters:

if (delayTimer < delay) {
            delayTimer += deltaMillis;
        } else { ... }

And this is the way you say we should update particles:

for (int i = effects.size - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    PooledEffect effect = effects.get(i);
    effect.draw(batch, delta);
    if (effect.isComplete()) {
        effect.free();
        effects.removeIndex(i);
    }
}

What can and will happen (it happened to me) is that, after the update, in the random case in which "delayTimer += deltaMillis;" will be greater or equal than delay, isComplete will return true, even if the effect is continuous, and if we free/remove all particles which are complete just like in the cycle above, we will end up removing random continuous effects that should not be removed.

